// itm files
@1000 = ~Poisoned Arrow~
@1001 = ~This arrow is coated with a dangerous poison that cannot be removed by ordinary means. You are to bring the arrow to Alatoasz Berendim in Duskwood Dell, Eldath’s sacred sanctuary, so that the poison may be studied and its origin traced.~
@1002 = ~Groveglove~
@1003 = ~The Groveglove is an exceptionally rare flowering plant whose waxy, foxglove-like bells bloom in shimmering hues ranging from deep violet to pale pink. It grows only in ancient, magic-laden elven groves, often near still spring pools or within the boundaries of a Mythal.

A single drop of sap is enough to kill an adult—or, in skilled hands, to craft a cure for equally lethal afflictions. Druids regard the plant with ambivalence: as a natural part of the world’s balance, but also as a reminder that even the most beautiful gifts of nature can be deadly.

You must deliver one of these blossoms to Alatoasz Berendim in Duskwood Dell.~
@1004 = ~Fungal Key~
@1005 = ~This key is overgrown with grime and strange spores. It appears to open a very particular kind of door.~
@1006 = ~Supplier's Note~
@1007 = ~Skann, I need you to deliver a large shipment of my work to several interested parties. Meet me at the marked location at Toadstool Hollow. Destroy this note so it doesn’t fall into the wrong hands.

Delgorth~
@1008 = ~Keltormir, the Fallen Empire~
@1009 = ~Keltormir, the Fallen Empire
by Elenneth Moonsyl, Sage of Evereska

"All forests remember. Even when the trees fall and the songs fade, the roots hold the memory."

In the elder days of Toril, long before the rise of Calimshan or Tethyr, the ancient forest empire of Keltormir stretched across the south of Faerûn. Bound by reverence to the Seldarine and governed by harmony with nature, the elves of Keltormir built their realms in communion with the surrounding land.

Among the most enduring legacies of Keltormir were its three mythal-guarded cities, each a beacon of elven magic and culture; each now lost, faded, and fallen: Myth Rhynn, Myth Unnohyr and Myth Tellaren.

Myth Rhynn
Hidden deep within the Mytharan Woods, in the shadowed reaches of the Wealdath, lies Myth Rhynn, a hallowed necropolis of the elves. Its mythal, unlike those of other elven cities, was wrought for reverence. But the mythal is broken. Whether shattered by age, sacrilege, or forgotten sorrow, it no longer binds the dead to sleep. Now, shadows walk among the roots of ancient barrows, and unquiet spirits rise in the stillness. Even the elves who once came to honor their ancestors now avoid the place, for the broken threads of the mythal pull at their hearts, as if mourning its own fall. What was once a sacred resting place is now a sorrowful wound upon the forest.

Myth Unnohyr
Myth Unnohyr rose in the shadowed valleys of Keltormir’s southern forests. Its magic once fostered growth, healing, and deep communion with the natural world. Yet, something began to unravel. Elven lore speaks in hushed tones of a faltering divine bond—of a protector whose waning strength left the city's heart exposed. When that sacred power faded, the mythal shattered in silent despair, birthing a zone of wild and dead magic—a festering wound upon the Weave that endures to this day. Now, few dare to approach its ruins, where even divine power falters, and the poisoned soil hums with restless malice.

Myth Tellaren
Far to the south, in lands now buried under the sands of the desert, stood Myth Tellaren. When the genie-lords of Calim and Memnon warred across the south, their chaos reached even the hidden places of the elves. Myth Tellaren’s mythal, strained by the genies' pressure, fractured. And with it, the delicate magic that held the city aloft. Some say the ruin still exists beneath the shifting sands, frozen in a moment of magical collapse—its mythal broken, yet still pulsing faintly, like embers beneath ash.

Though Keltormir has faded into myth, the echoes of its greatness endure. Where trees grow thick and stars fall strangely, where magic sings through stone or refuses to stir—there, the empire of leaves once stood. And perhaps, may rise again.~
@1010 = ~Fragment of an Amulet~
@1011 = ~This is a fragment of a pendant, depicting three intertwined golden rings—a sacred symbol once revered by an ancient elven guardian of magic and unity. Though incomplete, the fragment still resonates faintly with the corrupted mythal of Myth Unnohyr. When held, you feel the oppressive forces around you soften slightly. Yet without the full amulet, its protective strength remains useless.~
@1012 = ~Head of an Elf~
@1013 = ~This is the severed head of what was once a strikingly handsome elven man. Around his neck, strands of long, silken hair remain tightly coiled—still clinging to him in death. It appears he was strangled… not by rope or cord, but by someone’s hair.~  
@1014 = ~Golden Chain~
@1015 = ~This is a finely wrought golden chain, crafted with meticulous care to once bear a splendid amulet. Though the medallion itself has been lost to time, the chain retains a faint, lingering trace of its ancient enchantment—a forgotten duty to shield and preserve.~
@1016 = ~Mythrien's Amulet~
@1017 = ~Forged during the founding of Myth Unnohyr, this talisman bore the emblem of three intertwined rings, the symbol of the nearly forgotten elven god of mythals, Mythrien Sarath. Even as centuries of ruin dulled its brilliance, the talisman preserves a fragile echo of its former strength. In the presence of this relic, the wild surges and dead magic of the broken mythal falter, offering protection to those who walk the city's shattered streets.

Equipped abilities: 
– Immunity to wild magic and dead magic zone effects in Myth Unnohyr

Weight: 0~
@1018 = ~Necklace of Life~
@1019 = ~Simple in appearance, yet suffused with quiet power, this necklace pulses faintly with restorative energy. Though its origins remain unclear, it is often favored by healers, peacewardens, and those who walk where death's shadow lingers.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Saving Throw vs. Necromancy: +5  
– Maximum Hit Points: +2  

Weight: 0~
@1020 = ~Potion of Peace~
@1021 = ~Drawn from a spring where Eldath’s blessing flows undisturbed, this sacred draught carries more than mere healing. Those who drink of it feel restored and unburdened—as though a gentle current carried their troubles away.

STATISTICS:

Special: Cures poison and disease, removes curses, and heals 5 Hit Points

Weight: 1~
@1022 = ~Holy Water of Eldath~
@1023 =~This is a carafe of holy water of Eldath. It is one of the ingredients needed to create an antidote for the poison created by the priest of Talona.
  
STATISTICS:

Weight: 1~
@1024 = ~Will-o'-wisp's attack~
@1025 = ~Will-o'-pox's attack~

@1030 = ~Spectre's Ring~
@1031 = ~Helmet~
@1032 = ~Helmet of Elven Chants~
@1033 = ~This helmet is known as the Helmet of Elven Chants. Forged by a master elven smith, it resonates with the ancient harmonies of his people. When worn by an elf, it enhances their natural gifts and allows the bearer to invoke an age-old elven chant that lends its strength to them and their allies.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Protects against critical hits
– Dexterity: +2 (elves only), +1 (half-elves only)

Charge abilities:
– May cast Chant once per day

Weight: 0~

@1037 = ~Ioun Stone~
@1038 = ~Berry-Shaped Ioun Stone~
@1039 = ~This Ioun stone is shaped like a berry. Someone must have used magic to make it look like this.
  
STATISTICS:

Weight: 0~
@1040 = ~This Ioun stone is believed to have been created by a powerful cleric of Talona. Shaped like a sour green berry, it carries a sharp, unripe scent that lingers unpleasantly in the air.

Certain Talonites used stones like this to deal with rival priests—especially those who stood in the way of their poison-laced ambitions. Unsurprisingly, the stone refuses to attune to those of a good-aligned nature.

STATISTICS:

Combat abilities:
– THAC0 vs. Clerics: +3

Special abilities:
– When carried or equipped, this Ioun stone dispels the poisonous fumes blocking the entrance to the tower in Myth Unnohyr

Weight: 0~
@1041 = ~Studded Leather~
@1042 = ~The Blessed Wyvern +3~
@1043 = ~This studded leather armor is known under the name The Blessed Wyvern and it is believed to protect its wearer by granting <PRO_HIMHER> regeneration, but it's also able to manipulate the probability thus it grants its user a boost of luck.
  
Some say it was named after a wyvern called Lucretia.
  
STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities: 
– Luck: +1
– Regenerates 1 Hit Point per round

Armor Class: 4 (2 vs. slashing, 3 vs. piercing and missile)
Requires:
 6 Strength

Weight: 8~
@1044 = ~Celestial Antidote~
@1045 = ~Celestial Antidote~
@1046 = ~This is the antidote you brewed in the Talonite’s cauldron beneath Myth Unnohyr. It is said to cure those afflicted by the potent toxin distilled from the strange flowers that grow among the ruins.
  
STATISTICS:

Weight: 1~
@1047 = ~Cloak~
@1048 = ~Eldath's Embrace~
@1049 = ~This enchanted cloak dates back to a reclusive priest of Eldath who wandered the groves of Wealdath in ages past. Birds would nest in his hands, wolves guarded his sleep, and even the most skittish beasts would draw near to bask in his tranquil presence.
When he passed from the world, it is said dryads wove this mantle from the leaves that had fallen around his resting place. Those who wear it walk in quiet grace—and the wild things of the world walk beside them.
  
STATISTICS:

Charge abilities:
– May cast Protection From Evil, 10' Radius once per day (on self)

Equipped abilities:
– Armor Class: +2
– Saving Throws: +2
– Move Silently: +10%
– 5% chance to cast Sanctuary when the cloak’s wearer is hit in combat.
– When animals are within 10 feet:
 - Additional +1 to AC
 - Additional +1 to Saving Throws
 - Immunity to Fear effects

Weight: 3~
@1050 = ~Redhive Flower~
@1051 = ~This beautiful, sweet-scented flower is a gift from a boy living in Duskwood Dell to his aunt in Athkatla’s Government District. He asks you to deliver the flower along with a message: That he is safe, and simply needs some time apart.

STATISTICS:
Weight: 1~
@1052 = ~Earthworm~
@1053 = ~This earthworm smells of wet ground and... pumpkins. It looks very pink and it acts quite lively. Apart from that, there is nothing unusual about it.
  
STATISTICS: 

Weight: 0~
@1054 = ~Emblem~
@1055 = ~Holy Symbol of Eldath~
@1057 = ~This is a simple emblem depicting Eldath's symbol, carved with care and reverence. Though unassuming in appearance, it seems to offer quiet protection to those who honor the goddess of peace. Its influence subtly guides the bearer away from aggression—enhancing defense while diminishing the drive to strike.
  
STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Armor Class: +1
– Saving Throws: +1
– THAC0: -2

Weight: 0~
@1058 = ~Shield Fragment~
@1059 = ~This appears to be the central piece of a shield. Without the outer frame, however, it is unusable.
  
STATISTICS:

Weight: 0~
@1060 = ~This appears to be the central piece of a shield. Without the outer frame, however, it is unusable.
  
STATISTICS:

Weight: 0~
@1061 = ~This appears to be the outer frame of a shield. Without its central component, however, it is unusable.
  
STATISTICS:

Weight: 0~
@1062 = ~Buckler~
@1063 = ~The Leafrunner +3~
@1064 = ~This elegant buckler once belonged to a druid-guardian named Blasanna Leafrunner, from whom it takes its name. When a gnoll warband threatened her grove and kin, Blasanna stood alone before them. Legends tell that she moved with the swiftness of a storm wind, striking down half the invaders before the rest fled in terror.

Some claim her speed came from the buckler itself, its magic lending her the grace of the wild. Others believe it was the forest’s own spirit that bore her onward, unwilling to see its protector fall.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Armor Class: +4
– No protection against missile and piercing attacks
– Movement rate increased by 1; increased by 2 in forests
– Saving Throws vs. Invocation School: +2

Requires:
 4 Strength

Weight: 2~
@1065 = ~Herbal Brew in a Mug~
@1066 = ~This brew is made of chamomile, wild honey, blackberry and lavender. It's supposed to calm people down. You are to bring this brew to the sirine by the water in Duskwood Dell, so that she may find peace.
  
STATISTICS: 

Weight: 2~
@1067 = ~Delgorth's Note~
@1068 = ~First Entry:
The Groveglove... the legends were true. It blooms still amidst the shattered remnants of Myth Unnohyr, where dead magic festers and life warps. Talona smiles upon my discovery!

Second Entry:
With painstaking effort, I have distilled the first batches of the toxin. Small quantities only—precious drops of death, born of the Vein’s purple heart. Already, the results have exceeded expectations: swift, incurable, a silencer of both flesh and spirit.

Third Entry:
My first shipments have been delivered to certain enemies of the Harpers. Petty lords, disillusioned sellswords, and those who see the Harpers' meddling as a threat to true balance. Let the self-righteous choke on their piousness.

Fourth Entry:
The Night Masks in Westgate see potential. They offer coin and bodies to spread the work, but they lack subtlety. I must tread carefully. The Zhentarim, ever watchful, may prove useful—if kept at arm’s length.

Fifth Entry:
The foundations here in Myth Unnohyr are firm enough—its wild and dead magic shields my work from unwanted eyes. Though I have managed to cultivate a few vines within the dead soil, they grow slowly, stubbornly, yielding but scant blossoms. At this rate, it will take seasons to produce enough toxin for the ambitions I nurture. I must seek a way to quicken their growth—or secure more hands willing to tend the harvest.

Sixth Entry:
This Eldathyn interfered, and paid for his foolishness. Others may come, but the path is clear: the toxin will spread. It will seep into the veins of Faerûn’s mighty and humble alike. Talona’s will is woven into every trembling breath they take.

Let the strong fall and the weak wither. Only decay is eternal!

— Malagent Delgorth
~
@1075 = ~Headband~
@1076 = ~Halo of Coagulated Blood~
@1077 = ~Fashioned from congealed, hardened blood clots, this halo once adorned the brow of an ancient blood amniote imprisoned beneath Myth Unnohyr. It is not merely a crown, but a scar given shape, memory turned weapon.

STATISTICS:

Combat abilities:
– When the wearer kills a creature, <PRO_HESHE> gains 1 temporary hit point for 1 turn (cumulative).

Equipped abilities:
– Charisma: –1
– Acid Resistance: +10%
– 25% chance that an attacker striking the wearer suffers 1d2 acid damage (Save vs. Death at –2 negates)

Weight: 1
~
@1078 = ~Dagger~
@1079 = ~Scolopendra's Spit +3~
@1080 = ~This finely wrought dagger is a favored weapon among spellcasters, especially those who command acidic conjurations and projectiles. It enhances the wielder’s casting abilities and allows <PRO_HIMHER> to strike foes from a distance.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Decrease spellcasting time by 1
– Immunity to poison

Combat abilities:
– Acid Damage dealt: +10%
– Does allow to make both melee and ranged attacks

THAC0: +3
Damage (melee): 1d4+3 (piercing), +1 Acid damage
Damage (ranged): 1d4+3 (acid)
Speed Factor: 1
Proficiency Type: Dagger
Type: One-handed
Requires:
 3 Strength

Weight: 1
~
@1084 = ~Staff~
@1085 = ~Branch of Duskwood Dell +3~
@1086 = ~This quarterstaff still carries a faint verdant sheen. It was never meant to kill, but to clear the way and to preserve. Its magic shields the bearer from all effects that would hinder <PRO_HISHER> steps or halt <PRO_HISHER> journey. For those who wish only to walk their path in peace, it is a steadfast companion.

STATISTICS:

Charge abilities:
– May cast Remove Paralysis once per day 

Equipped abilities:
– The wearer is immune to everything, magical and otherwise, that affects mobility in any way. This includes Haste and Slow spells.

THAC0: +3
Damage: 1d2 (non-lethal)
Speed Factor: 2
Proficiency Type: Quarterstaff
Type: Two-handed
Requires:
 5 Strength

Weight: 3
~
@1087 = ~Rose of Eldath~
@1088 = ~This is a rose blossom blessed by a priest of Eldath. When consumed, it restores the life energy of the afflicted, reversing any previous level drain caused by unnatural forces or undead creatures.

STATISTICS:

Special: Removes all level drain effects from the target

Weight: 1~
@1089 = ~Two-Handed Sword~
@1090 = ~Good Luck, Honeysuckle +3~
@1091 = ~This finely balanced two-handed sword once belonged to a ranger named Vala’ll Stormneedle, a beloved protector of the Larswood region. He was known not only for his skill in battle, but for the joy with which he lived—a perfect life, a loving family, and his wife named Systianna, a faithful of Tymora.

Before each mission, she would kiss his cheek and hand him the blade, whispering, "Good luck, honeysuckle." Unlike many folk heroes whose tales end in blood, the legend of Vala’ll is one of rare peace: He lived with Systianna until the age of eighty, passing neither to sword nor spell, but to pneumonia.

Some believe it was this very sword that shielded him all those years—a silent companion preserving his life long beyond the span of most who walk with steel in hand. 
  
STATISTICS:

Combat abilities:
– Each successful hit has a 15% chance to lower the target's Luck by 1 point for 2 rounds (Save vs. Spell at –4 negates), while increasing the wielder's Luck by 1 point for an entire day.

THAC0: +3
Damage: 1d10+3 (slashing)
Speed Factor: 7
Proficiency Type: Two-handed Sword
Type: Two-handed
Requires:
 14 Strength

Weight: 9~
@1092 = ~Light Crossbow~
@1093 = ~Thornshooter +1~
@1094 =~This unique crossbow conjures its own magical thorn-bolts: Sharp, barbed projectiles that can cause enemies to become entangled on impact.

Due to the nature of the druidic enchantments woven into the weapon, only single-class druids are able to wield it effectively.

STATISTICS:

Equipped Abilities:
– Sets Crossbow Proficiency to 1

Combat Abilities:
– Does not require ammunition; fires conjured magical thorn-bolts
– 20% chance per hit to entangle the target (Save vs. Spell at -1 negates)

THAC0: +1
Damage: 1d6+1 (missile)
Speed Factor: 4
Proficiency Type: Crossbow
Type: Two-handed
Requires:
 8 Strength

Weight: 6~

@1146 = ~To whomever finds this:

The Mythal that once protected Myth Unnohyr is shattered beyond recognition. Within these ruins, magic frays and collapses without warning—prayers go unanswered, spells twist or wither to nothing.

Yet not all is lost. Certain beings—Will-o'-Wisps among them—seem to have adapted to the Mythal’s corruption. Their resilience hints at the possibility that immunity is not impossible.

Before my strength failed me, I theorized that an ancient elven relic might be restored—one capable of channeling the original power of the Mythal to shield its bearer from its corruptive force. Perhaps spellcasting within these ruins could then be possible again.

I suspect that the essences of wisps born of both wild and dead magic, combined with the elven talisman itself, might yield such an effect. If such rare wisps truly dwell within these ruins, and if one could forge the ancient elven talisman, life of a mage here would be far less precarious.

Whether such a talisman can truly be made, I shall not live to see.

May you fare better than I.~
@1147 = ~Peacewalker's stories I~
@1148 = ~"The Still Water Within"

As penned by Lirael of the Gentle Banks, Keeper of the Silent Pool

I was but young when first I wandered deep into the Wood of Sharp Teeth.
The elders had warned me: "Not all who walk beneath the green honor life."
Yet my heart knew no fear, only the call to carry Eldath’s peace wherever my steps would take me.

For three nights I slept beneath the starlit canopy, the whispering leaves singing wind-songs to my soul. On the fourth evening, I came upon the ogre Brughul, who sought to feed his club with blood.

A calf, bound and trembling, lay near his fire. Brughul towered like two men, his club glistening with old stains. I could have fled. I could have struck with spell or flame.

But I did what Eldath had always taught: I sat.

Simply that. Cross-legged. Palms open. Heart bare. And I began to sing the old lullaby of the quiet waters.

"No blood shall quench as calm as light,
Drawn from a spring so pure and bright.
No scream shall ever bring release,
let silence sow the seeds of peace."

Brughuls rage faltered. The monster stepped forward. I smelled his breath. His grip loosened. The club dropped to moss. Then — silence. Only the soft splash of the calf as it stumbled into shallow water and was gone.

When I opened my eyes, I was alone. They say a ring of white lilies grows there now, though none bloomed before.

(Although this item may hold cultural value, it appears neither magical nor useful in advancing your mission.)~
@1149 = ~Peacewalker's stories II~
@1150 = ~"The Thorn and the Dove"
As recorded by the Willowroot Circle

He walked barefoot across Amn. Brother Eolan—a freewalker of Eldath—carried no coin, no weapon, no map. Only a waterskin and a heart uncluttered by wrath. Where others turned blades upon strangers, he offered silence, and when the world scorned mercy, he extended his hand.

It was in the Gorge of the Fallen Idol that he was most sorely tested.

The gorge is cut deep into the foothills of the Small Teeth. Long ago, a statue of a forgotten god fell from the cliffs and shattered in the chasm below. Since then, the gorge has attracted those with dark intentions.

One such was Thornmaw, a scar-marked brigand queen. When Brother Eolan wandered into her domain, she and her kin saw him as prey.

But he made no plea, no argument. He simply knelt. In the dust at the edge of the shattered idol’s gaze, he drew forth his waterskin. With both hands, he offered it to her. His eyes met hers. And he spoke: "When did you last drink without fear?"

The others laughed. But Thornmaw did not. Her hand lingered at her belt, where her curved blade hung heavy with dried blood. She stepped forward. Took the waterskin. Drank.

Then she hurled it down into the gorge and turned away, saying: "Go."

And he did.

No one laid hand nor claw on him. He passed unscathed, vanishing into the southern passes like mist before dawn.

The next season, the fallen idol bore something new—a vine, delicate and green, curling up through its cracked stone lips. Water pooled near its base.

(Although this item may hold cultural value, it appears neither magical nor useful in advancing your mission.)~
