@1220 = ~Wish

Wish will fulfill literally the utterance of the caster. Thus, the actuality of the past, present, or future might be altered in some limited manner. The greater the wish, the greater the strain upon the fabric of reality, and the greater the chance of unwanted consequences.

Curiously, this particular scroll may be read by anyone — not merely those trained in the arcane arts. Its words are written in a language so simple, so clear, that even the unlearned might speak them aloud with ease. Almost too simple, in fact... too easy to believe.~
@1221 = ~Wisdom point lost~
@1222 = ~Torn Page I~
@1223 = ~These torn and faded pages appear to be fragments from a much larger chronicle concerning the history of Myth Unnohyr. The ink is elven, the script elegant yet frayed by time:

"From the Days of Founding - Year of the First Flowering

And so was the City of Quiet Radiance laid upon the forest glade, where seven ley-lines met and the breeze whispered in the tongue of the ancients. The High Mages of Unnohyr bound the first stones with silver word and living root, and the skies turned blue and deep in their blessing.

Mythrien Sarath, Lord of Wards, cast down his gaze and was pleased. His touch fell like dew upon the high towers, and from that day forward the Mythal shielded the city with light and serenity. May all conflict break and wash away before our walls, the Founding Oath proclaimed.

And for a time, so it was."

Though they seem of no direct use to your quest, the words may help you understand the deeper nature of what transpired here — and what was lost.~
@1224 = ~Torn Page II~
@1225 = ~These torn and faded pages appear to be fragments from a much larger chronicle concerning the history of Myth Unnohyr. The ink is elven, the script elegant yet frayed by time:

"In the height of Myth Unnohyr’s glory, an elven high mage sought to bind his soul to the city’s Mythal. He wished not for wisdom, nor for legacy — but for unending life, carried from vessel to vessel by the spell’s eternal weave. 

Yet in doing so, he wounded the very heart of the Mythal. Life and death bled together, and when his body fell, the Mythal itself raised him anew — each time within another fallen elf.
Thus was born the undying echo of a guardian who betrayed his own vow. His immortality became the city’s curse, and his rebirth its unending decay"

Though they seem of no direct use to your quest, the words may help you understand the deeper nature of what transpired here — and what was lost.~
@1226 = ~Signet Ring of House Vemmil~
@1227 = ~This opulent signet ring bears the crest of the Vemmil family, an ancient Amnian merchant line known for its wealth, political maneuvering, and staggering lack of humility. Among Amnian elites, its wearer is often greeted with smiles – genuine or not – and a careful counting of silverware.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Immunity to poison

Charge abilities:
– Cast Friends once per day
  Area of Effect: self

Weight: 1~
@1228 = ~Blade of Day and Night~
@1229 = ~Forged in the elder days of Myth Unnohyr, this elegant longsword was once a ceremonial weapon of the elven guardians who served the Watcher Over Mythals. Known as the Blade of Day and Night, it was said to embody the balance between vigilance and rest, between the radiance of the sun and the quiet strength of moonlight.

Legends tell that the sword shattered when the city’s protective mythal began to wane, its twin halves cast apart by opposing forces of light and shadow. 

Now reforged, the sword shifts its nature with the turning of the heavens. In daylight it burns with quiet resolve, keen and strong. Under moon and stars, it softens its radiance, guarding the bearer with calm and patience.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– During day and dawn: +1 THAC0 and +1 Damage
– During night and dusk: +1 AC and +1 to all Saving Throws

THAC0: +3
Damage: 2d4+3 (slashing)
Speed Factor: 5
Proficiency Type: Bastard Sword
Type: One-handed
Requires:
 11 Strength

Weight: 7~
@1230 = ~Part of a Blade~
@1231 = ~This is part of a blade. The metal shimmers with a bluish hue, flecked with tiny motes that gleam like stars in the night sky. Without the other half of the sword—and someone skilled enough to reforge them together—this piece is of little use.~
@1232 = ~This is part of a blade. The metal gleams with a radiant golden light, bright as the rays of the sun. Without the other half of the sword—and someone skilled enough to reforge them together—this piece is of little use.~
@1233 = ~Nightblade~
@1234 = ~Dayblade~
@1235 = ~This is part of a legendary elven sword known as the "Blade of Day and Night". This fragment is the Nightblade. The metal shimmers with a bluish hue, flecked with tiny motes that gleam like stars in the night sky. Without the other half of the sword—and someone skilled enough to reforge them together—this piece is of little use.~
@1236 = ~This is part of a legendary elven sword known as the "Blade of Day and Night". This fragment is the Dayblade. The metal gleams with a radiant golden light, bright as the rays of the sun. Without the other half of the sword—and someone skilled enough to reforge them together—this piece is of little use.~

@1237 = ~Marrik, 
we’re behind the Temple of Helm in the Bridge District after dark, like every night. Bring the token, and you’ll get what you’ve been asking for.~
@1238 = ~Old Coin~
@1239 = ~This worn coin bears the faint image of an elderly man with a solemn expression. The details have long since faded — the nose smoothed by countless hands, the edges dulled by time. There are no markings of mint or value, and yet it feels heavier than it should, as if it remembers the years it has passed through. Whoever pressed it into shape is long gone, and whatever purpose it once held has long been forgotten.~

@1240 = ~Bottle of Pixie Dust~
@1241 = ~This small bottle contains a handful of shimmering pixie dust that can be tossed into the air. Any ally touched by the dust becomes invisible (the dust spreads in a radius of about 15 ft.). Of course, the invisible creature is not magically silenced, and certain other conditions can still reveal it. Even allies cannot see the invisible creature or its gear unless they are normally able to see invisible things or employ magic to do so. Items dropped or set down by the invisible creature become visible, while items picked up vanish if tucked into the creature’s clothing or pouches.

The dust’s magic lasts until it is dispelled, willingly ended, or broken by an attack. It can also fade naturally after 24 hours. The invisible being may move freely and cast defensive spells, but any offensive action immediately ends the effect — though it still allows the first strike to go unseen.~
@1242 = ~Arrow of healing~
@1243 = ~These arrows are an invention of Eldath’s faithful. Each shaft bears a small vial of sanctified water drawn from a sacred spring. When the arrow strikes, the vial shatters, releasing a gentle burst of divine essence that seeps into the wounded flesh of its target.

Though the arrows are crafted for healing, even a gentle strike can bruise or cut when loosed from a powerful bow — a small price to pay for the healing they bestow.

STATISTICS:

THAC0: +1 
Launcher: Bow
Special: Restores 4d6 Hit Points to the creature struck

Weight: 0~
@1244 = ~Axe of Apologies~
@1245 = ~This magical battle axe bears the image of an orc. Once wielded by the Odonti, a reclusive clan of peaceful orcs from the Unapproachable East who venerate Eldath, it served as a symbol of regret.

The axe whispers a soft "Sorry!" each time it strikes a target. Unfortunately, these apologies weigh heavier on the wielder than on the enemy, instilling a subtle sense of guilt that disrupts <PRO_HISHER> focus in battle.
When the bearer is wounded, the axe seems to grieve—sometimes knitting flesh with Eldathyn blessings.


STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities: 
– 25% chance to cast Cure Moderate Wounds on the wielder when hit

Combat abilities:
– Each successful hit causes the wielder to suffer a cumulative –2 THAC0 for 2 rounds

THAC0: +2
Damage: 1d8+2 (slashing)
Speed Factor: 5
Proficiency Type: Axe
Type: One-handed
Requires:
 10 Strength

Weight: 5~
@1246 = ~Freewalker's sandals~
@1247 = ~These simple leather sandals protect the wearer on <PRO_HISHER> peaceful journey. Favored by those who walk without violence and stop for no one, they ensure that no step need be delayed.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Immune to Entangle and Web

Weight: 4
~
@1248 = ~Ring of Non-Detection~
@1249 = ~Fashioned by a reclusive cabal, this simple band was designed to shield their agents from arcane prying. When worn, it shrouds the bearer in subtle counter-magic that prevents detection by spells.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– While hidden or invisible, the wearer is non-detectable by magical means such as Detect Invisibility and scrying

Weight: 0~
@1250 = ~Blinding Powder~
@1251 = ~This powder can be thrown at any creature within 40 ft. Upon impact, it dissipates in a 15-ft. radius and blinds all creatures caught within. A saving throw vs. Breath Weapon -2 negates the effect. A blinded creature suffers a –4 penalty to attack rolls and Armor Class for one turn.~

// script strings
@2000 = ~Duskwood Dell~
@2001 = ~Eldath, goddess of peace and calm waters~
@2002 = ~A profound sense of peace washes over you in this place. You feel utterly incapable of raising a weapon here.~
@2003 = ~As you approach the gate leading to the lower levels, you feel a flicker of magic. It seems the corrupted mythal does not reach into the depths—meaning your magic should function normally in the areas below.~
@2004 = ~Upon entering the ruined elven city, you feel the shattered remnants of the mythal coil around you—its once-pure magic now twisted into a volatile blend of wild surges and dead magic.~
@2005 = ~You must place both pieces of a necklace upon the anvil to reforge them into one.~
@2006 = ~With the aid of the magical anvil, you are able to reforge the two pieces into one once more.~
@2007 = ~Could it be you... my beloved, at last?~
@2008 = ~The corrupted mythal does not reach this place.~
@2009 = ~(You feel the pull of the berry-shaped Ioun stone towards the tower. It may be a sign you are now able to enter its walls.)~
@2010 = ~(You do not have the berry-shaped Ioun stone. You can no longer enter the tower. Without the stone, the barrier is erected.)~
@2011 = ~A small jeweler’s anvil rests atop a larger one. Fragments of fine chains lie scattered nearby, as though many necklaces were once forged here. Strangely, the anvil radiates strong magic that seems untouched by the corrupted mythal.~
@2012 = ~None of the items in your inventory appear suitable for crafting a necklace upon this anvil.~
@2013 = ~Magic seems to function normally within this area.~
@2014 = ~This statue depicts an elven deity, but you find it difficult to recognize it.~
@2015 = ~This statue portrays Mythrien Sarath, a nearly forgotten god once revered for his guardianship over Mythals.~
@2016 = ~You recognize this statue as likely depicting Mythrien Sarath—a nearly forgotten elven god.~
@2017 = ~I AM THE POISON AND I SHALL DEVOUR YOU!~
@2018 = ~You hear a faint sound rising from the cauldron. It seems that with the creature’s death, an antidote has formed within.~
@2019 = ~Rose... it must be safe!~
@2020 = ~Take it to Mythrien! Place it under his feet and reach for his helping hand!~
@2021 = ~When you approach the ruins, you notice an ankheg that looked as if it was lured by the place, but when the creature notices you, it decides to attack.~  
@2022 = ~A statue of a young elven warrior-maiden, red roses blooming at her feet — the only plants untouched by the corrupted Mythal.~
@2023 = ~It seems you require something else to forge an amulet that shields you from the Mythal—apparently, an essence.~

@2024 = ~Blood... All I can see is blood!~
@2025 = ~Free me! Please!~
@2026 = ~(The yuan-ti is nowhere to be seen, but he couldn't have left Myth Unnohyr, he was too wounded for that.)~
@2027 = ~You're in Myth Unnohyr again. The path behind you is sealed by a wall of tangled growth. Your only escape lies ahead, through the heart of the shattered city.~
@2028 = ~Something unsettling stirs in the north. To reach it, you must pass through the sanctuary once claimed by the priest of Talona.~
@2029 = ~We should see our dryad-friend first. From what I understand, she has the sword.~
@2030 = ~We came for the Remembrance of the Myths, my friend. The High Priest knows about everything.~
@2031 = ~Yes. I know. And I was told to give you the sword. Even though I believe it should stay here. With me.~
@2032 = ~We do not have much choice.~
@2033 = ~There is always a choice.~
@2034 = ~Here. Take it. And I pray it won't become your doom. May Eldath watch over you.~
@2035 = ~Now I will send you to the hidden entrance of Myth Unnohyr, <CHARNAME>.~
@2036 = ~Farewell. May Eldath’s quiet breath shelter you.~
@2037 = ~Find our enemy, <CHARNAME>. Find the wyrd and use this sword against it. It should also break the barrier and let you leave that damned place.~
@2038 = ~We'll wait for your return.~
@2039 = ~If anyone is to win this battle, it's you.~
@2040 = ~The path behind you is sealed by a wall of tangled growth. Your only escape lies ahead, through the heart of the shattered city.~
@2041 = ~The entrance to this tower is shrouded in an unnatural mist. Without the proper means, you will not be able to enter.~

// ACPP 77 strings
@2042 = ~A proud elven warrior-maiden stands joyfully before her city.~
@2043 = ~She fights against numerous beasts.~
@2044 = ~The elven warrior-maiden appears to be stabilizing some magic.~
@2045 = ~An elven community mourns at a coffin.~

@2046 = ~You recognize Elv-Esster Aened, commander of the guard of Myth Unnohyr. She stands before the city – young, proud, and filled with hope.~
@2047 = ~She fights against numerous beasts – it seems the god Malar has a hand in this. Elv-Esster faces them alone – unyielding, without fear.~
@2048 = ~You realize she is trying to stabilize the failing mythal with her own essence – an act of sacrifice and magic.~
@2049 = ~The mourning elves in this image are not just witnesses to death, but to divine failure. Some lower their heads – others gaze accusingly at the sky.~

@2050 = ~An undead creature appears to be possessing an elf.~
@2051 = ~The elven warrior-maiden tries to drive back the undead.~
@2052 = ~The elven warrior-maiden seems to be torn apart by a blinding magical light.~

@2053 = ~Elv-Esster Aened's tomb~

@2054 = ~A ghostly entity cloaked in shadows appears to invade the body of a dying elf.~
@2055 = ~Elv-Esster Aened and her kin stand against the encroaching undead, their spells lashing out in desperation.~
@2056 = ~A surge of wild magic erupts as the mythal shatters—Elv-Esster vanishes within the blinding light.~

// ACPP70 strings - the tree obstacle
@2060 = ~By the power of the wardstone, the throng of undead trees is banished.~
@2061 = ~You could try to move this mighty tree aside using an object, fire, or exceptionally great strength.~
@2062 = ~With sheer force, you actually manage to shift the tree aside.~
@2063 = ~You could try to move this mighty tree aside using an object, fire, or exceptionally great strength.~
@2064 = ~The tree collapses under the fire and dissolves.~
@2065 = ~The fire seems to slowly destroy the fallen tree.~
@2066 = ~The fire seems to have some effect on the fallen tree.~
@2067 = ~Now that the passage is clear, the wardstone crumbles to dust.~

@2068 = ~Temple of Mythrien~
@2069 = ~Mmm... oh-ho-ho! Hmmm. Such sweetness! Crunchy comb, golden nectar... *slurp* Ahhh, bliss indeed!~ [AC#PPHO0]
@2070 = ~Oh! By the Gentle Broodkeeper herself... I did not expect company while I indulged.~

@2071 = ~From all you’ve learned, this statue appears to depict Commander Elv-Esster Aened, once the leader of Myth Unnohyr’s guard.~
@2072 = ~The dead magic zone prevents the trap from triggering properly.~
@2073 = ~Follow me.~

@2074 = ~You need all blessings to perform the ritual required to create the antidote.~

@2075 = ~Though the water is murky, you notice a tunnel beneath the surface of the water. You could dive through and explore it if you wish.~

// the two fairies
@2100 = ~If you must sparkle, do it over there!~
@2101 = ~But over there is boring!~
@2102 = ~Stop tugging my robe!~
@2103 = ~Fine, fine! We’ll tug your hair instead. Happy now?~
@2104 = ~Don’t trust fireflies. They’re just show-offs with no style.~

@2105 = ~Now that you're safe, please— no more vanishing without a word!~
@2106 = ~But then who would you worry about, Brother Edrim? We keep your heart healthy!~
@2107 = ~It’s truly wonderful to have you back!~
@2108 = ~Oh really? We’ll remind you of that next time we’re tugging on your robe!~

@2200 = ~Infirmary~
@2201 = ~Temple of Eldath~
@2202 = ~Tree of Nourishment~
@2203 = ~Eldath’s Grotto~
@2204 = ~High Fallskeeper’s Tree~



















